  <div class="about sec">
    <div class="sec-t">About</div>
    <p>Grünerløkka (colloquially "Løkka") is a residential and commercial district on the east bank of the <strong>Akerselva river</strong>, approximately 1.5–2 km northeast of Oslo Central Station. The area takes its name from Friedrich Grüner, who owned farmland here in the 17th century. During the industrial expansion of the second half of the 1800s, it developed as a working-class neighbourhood of factory workers and artisans. The district is part of Oslo's largest protected urban area. Today it is bounded by the river to the west, Sofienberg to the east, and the Vulkan district to the south. The main commercial street is <strong>Thorvald Meyers gate</strong>, with the parallel <strong>Markveien</strong> also lined with shops and cafés.</p>
    <p>The district contains several parks: <strong>Birkelunden</strong> (host to the weekly Sunday flea market and historically significant as one of Oslo's first public parks) and <strong>Sofienberg Park</strong> to the east. The converted Vulkan industrial complex to the south contains <strong>Mathallen Oslo</strong>, a food hall in a renovated factory building with Norwegian and international food stalls. The Akerselva river walk follows both banks through the district and continues north through waterfalls and former mill sites. Street murals are found along Brenneriveien and Ingens gate. <strong>Parkteatret</strong> — originally built as Norway's first cinema in 1907 — operates as a live music venue on Olaf Ryes plass.</p>
    <p>Trams 11, 12, and 13 serve Grünerløkka via stops at Schous plass, Olaf Ryes plass, and Birkelunden on Thorvald Meyers gate. From Jernbanetorget (Oslo Central Station), Tram 12 takes approximately 10 minutes to Birkelunden. Bus 30 also serves the area. The district is a 15–20 minute walk from Oslo Central Station. The Oslo Botanical Garden (Botanisk hage) is located a short walk east of the district. The MUNCH museum is approximately 15 minutes south on foot via the Akerselva path.</p>
  </div>

