    <div class="sec-t">FAQ</div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">Is Grünerløkka free to visit?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Yes. Grünerløkka is a public neighbourhood. All streets, parks including Birkelunden and Sofienberg Park, and the Akerselva riverside path are free to access at all times. Individual cafés, restaurants, shops, and venues charge their own prices. No entry ticket or guided tour is required to explore the area.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">How do I get to Grünerløkka by public transport?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Trams 11, 12, and 13 serve the neighbourhood, stopping at Schous plass, Olaf Ryes plass, and Birkelunden along Thorvald Meyers gate. From Jernbanetorget (Oslo Central Station), take Tram 12 towards Kjelsås — journey time is approximately 10 minutes to Birkelunden. The district is also a 15–20 minute walk from Oslo Central Station. Plan journeys at ruter.no.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">When is the Grünerløkka flea market?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">A weekly flea market takes place at Birkelunden park every Sunday. It is one of the largest second-hand markets in Oslo, with stalls selling clothing, books, records, and household items. The market is free to browse and runs year-round, weather permitting. It is typically busiest between 12:00 and 15:00.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">What is Mathallen and where is it?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Mathallen Oslo is a food hall in the Vulkan district, directly adjacent to Grünerløkka on the Akerselva riverbank. It is housed in a converted industrial building at Vulkan 5. Entry is free; individual stalls charge separately. Stalls include Norwegian cheeses, freshly baked bread, charcuterie, seafood, and international street food. Check mathallen.no for current opening hours.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">What is the Akerselva river walk?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">The Akerselva is a river running south through Oslo from Maridalsvannet lake to the fjord at Bjørvika. A continuous pedestrian and cycling path follows both banks through Grünerløkka, passing converted factory buildings, waterfalls, and green riverside spaces. The path is free, open at all hours, and connects the neighbourhood to the MUNCH museum and Oslo Fjord to the south, and to the Botanical Garden and beyond to the north.</div>
